WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.640
Thank you, everyone, for attending. This will be the first in a series of three webinars

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:15.280
that focuses on how to use reproducibility in a business setting. And the real gist of

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:19.500
what we're doing here is, over the past few years, as you may know, academics have been

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:24.959
very concerned with the problem of reproducibility in data science research. Here's just one

00:00:24.959 --> 00:00:29.180
of many headlines that the public has read about reproducibility. This one comes from

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:35.099
Forbes. But there's been a quote-unquote reproducibility crisis in data science research. And there's

00:00:35.099 --> 00:00:40.639
been a lot of progress made to address that crisis. And from a technological standpoint,

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:44.480
the problem's been solved, in my opinion. But there are many cultural changes that still

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:50.259
need to be made. The cultural changes don't concern us so much as the technological solution.

00:00:50.259 --> 00:00:54.320
The new technology that data scientists are using to make their work reproducible has

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.880
created unintentional benefits for people who use data science in a business setting.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:04.120
And that's what these webinars will look at. The first webinar, which you're at today,

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:08.879
is reproducibility in production. And I'm going to talk about the technological solutions

00:01:08.879 --> 00:01:13.199
to the reproducibility crisis, specifically one type of technology that I'm going to call

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:17.839
computational documents, which are just documents with executable code inside of them. I'll

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:21.919
show you how you can use those to create opportunities both for yourself and the people who consume

00:01:21.919 --> 00:01:27.360
your data science intelligence, whether that's customers, clients, bosses, colleagues, so

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:32.400
on. In the second webinar on September 18th, Thomas Mock will talk about RStudio Connect

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:36.519
in production. RStudio Connect is a production platform that allows you to share the types

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:40.720
of documents that we'll be talking about today. And it really completes the circle in terms

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:46.879
of providing opportunities and advantages in an everyday business situation. In the

00:01:46.879 --> 00:01:51.199
final webinar, Kelly O'Brien will talk about interactivity, which is probably the largest

00:01:51.199 --> 00:01:55.599
opportunity created by the technology of computational documents. She'll go over the

00:01:55.599 --> 00:01:59.760
best practices for making interactive material and tell you the things that you should be

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:04.440
considering as you develop interactive material for others to consume. That webinar will take

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:12.160
place on October 2nd. So for today, let's start by looking at what computational documents

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.919
are. This is what I mean by computational document. Let me exit the slides for a moment.

00:02:16.919 --> 00:02:22.520
Let's go to RStudio. This is a computational document. It's just a regular document, a

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:30.039
file. You can see text in here. But it has executable code embedded throughout the file.

00:02:30.039 --> 00:02:35.080
And a computational document is just a document that contains executable code. And when you

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:40.360
can put executable code into a document, then you can allow the reader of the document to

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:45.639
run the code. And the code can do things for them. As someone who knows how to write code,

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:49.039
you could write whatever code you like to do whatever you want the reader to be able

00:02:49.039 --> 00:03:00.679
to do with your document. This document contains a data analysis, a very simple one, as a matter

00:03:00.679 --> 00:03:03.960
of fact. And the code here just recreates the analysis. And this is typical of what

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:07.800
computational documents do. They're a way to solve reproducibility crisis by putting

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:12.520
the actual reproducible data analysis in your report. So whoever you pass the report onto

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.520
has everything they need to recreate the data analysis. For example, I can run the

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:24.119
code that's in this document, these buttons, and reproduce the document as I go. So here

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:28.759
this analysis is making some graphs. We'll look at it in detail later. And then the other

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:33.080
thing that this particular type of document allows you to do is you can knit this report.

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:38.119
Both the text that the author wrote in the document and the code that runs the document

00:03:38.119 --> 00:03:41.800
is combined. And so we see the text here with the code results. And it creates

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:46.199
a finished presentation to pass on to someone who wants to know about our results, but maybe

00:03:46.199 --> 00:03:53.160
not about the code. So that's the gist of a computational document. It is something that

00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:58.199
can contain embedded code. And because it can do that, it can automatically reproduce

00:03:58.199 --> 00:04:03.320
the data analysis done with code. And you can see here how computational documents are

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.720
a definitive solution to the reproducibility crisis in data science. Everything we need

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:15.399
to reproduce our work is here. But because we're reproducing it with code, not only can

00:04:15.399 --> 00:04:20.040
we just simply reproduce analysis, we can reproduce the analysis automatically.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:25.959
That automation is what creates opportunities for businesses who want to use computational

00:04:25.959 --> 00:04:31.239
documents. And not only does it create opportunities, it's going to be a disruptive

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:36.279
technology that changes how you think about delivering and performing data science if you

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:42.200
deliver or perform or conduct data science as part of your job. To put that in perspective,

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:50.200
let me draw a historical analogy. Go back to the slides. This is a picture of the printing press.

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:53.320
The printing press, famous example of disruptive technology.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:58.600
When Johan Gunnberg introduced the printing press into Europe in 1439,

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:05.239
no one could really foresee the sort of changes that it would catalyze in society. Now,

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:10.119
the video here is stressing the reproducible aspect of the printing press, but that's actually

00:05:10.119 --> 00:05:14.600
a red herring. You know, monks can reproduce books by hand before anyone came along with

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:19.959
the printing press. What the printing press did to change society is it made the reproduction

00:05:19.959 --> 00:05:24.920
of books automatable. It took a little bit of initial setup, but after you did that, you could

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:31.399
automatically reproduce books. Now, compare that to a computational document. It takes a little bit

00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:36.839
of initial setup to write the document, to put the code you want inside the document, but after

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:42.679
you do that setup, reproducing the analysis or reproducing the tasks that the code does is

00:05:42.679 --> 00:05:47.320
automatable. You could pass that document on to someone who doesn't know how to use code.

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:53.640
They could automatically do what you designed that document to do. What sort of changes should

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:59.799
you expect this to trigger downstream? Well, again, consider the printing press. When it became

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:05.239
automatable to reproduce books, many things changed. For the first time in history, it was now

00:06:05.239 --> 00:06:09.959
profitable to create a book to sell, and that gave rise to a huge new industry, the publishing

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:16.600
industry, which is still with us today. For the first time in history, authors had considerable

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:22.119
economic and political power, and that triggered new laws, copyright laws, which protected authors

00:06:22.119 --> 00:06:26.760
from, you know, publishers and people trying to steal their work, and also censorship laws, which

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:33.399
protected the public, supposedly, from the authors. Another thing that's very prominent when

00:06:33.399 --> 00:06:38.040
people talk about printing press is, for the first time in history, the Bible was no longer a black

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:43.000
box. People could look at it without an intermediary in the form of a priest or the church,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.320
and they could develop new interpretations on what they were working with, and that led to

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:53.559
new conflicts. And then just more generally, after it became automatable to reproduce

00:06:53.559 --> 00:07:00.359
this sort of work, it became beneficial, perhaps for the first time, for the common person to learn

00:07:00.359 --> 00:07:06.519
how to read. I think some of these changes are things that we'll see on a much smaller scale

00:07:06.519 --> 00:07:10.200
as computational documents become more and more used in our fields.

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:17.239
There's two main benefits of computational documents that we're going to focus on today,

00:07:17.239 --> 00:07:22.440
and the first benefit is for authors. When you use computational documents to report your results

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:27.079
and to deliver the insights you develop with your data science, you can start reporting those

00:07:27.079 --> 00:07:32.839
results much more efficiently. You could reuse the same initial work, the same setup that you

00:07:32.839 --> 00:07:38.519
put into making one document, to create many, many documents. The second change that computational

00:07:38.519 --> 00:07:45.320
documents facilitate is for users. The people who consume your reports that you generate with

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:51.160
computational documents can interact with the content in new ways, ways that might be very

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:56.200
valuable to them, ways that they might be very excited to have and even willing to pay for.

00:07:56.920 --> 00:08:01.000
So we're going to look at how you could create computational documents that you could use

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
in either of these ways to make your life better.

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:10.040
For the remainder of the webinar, we'll look at R Markdown, which is a technology that makes it

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:15.079
easy to create computational documents. I'll give you some tips about the features of R Markdown

00:08:15.079 --> 00:08:20.040
that I think have the largest payoff for using computational documents in a sort of business

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:25.480
or production setting. And then finally, we'll think about how to include interactivity or not

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:30.359
include interactivity in the documents that you make. Now throughout this webinar and the two

00:08:30.359 --> 00:08:35.000
webinars that follow in the series, we're going to talk about the word production. Now I want to

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.719
be clear up front that production means different things to different people, and we're aware of

00:08:39.719 --> 00:08:44.280
that. So please don't be distracted by the word production if it shows up in these webinars.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.880
But that would just mean that these materials that we're showing you are ready to use

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:53.320
however you want to use them and with whoever you want to use them with.

00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:01.320
All right, so we've looked at the promise of computational documents.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:06.280
Now let's look at a way for you to make computational documents with R. There are

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:09.320
many different ways to make computational documents, but we're going to focus on just

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:16.440
one known as R Markdown. And again, I'll leave the slides and go to a demo here.

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:23.000
The example document I showed you earlier right here is an R Markdown document,

00:09:23.799 --> 00:09:29.559
and R Markdown documents are just plain text files, but they contain three different types

00:09:29.559 --> 00:09:34.919
of content. So if we look at this file here, you'll see up here as the file extension.rmd.

00:09:34.919 --> 00:09:41.239
Don't let that fool you. Everything in this file is just a character and a plain character at that.

00:09:41.239 --> 00:09:48.359
So this is a plain text file that makes it easy to edit, to save. If you wanted to use version

00:09:48.359 --> 00:09:53.640
control on this file, say I have this file saved, so if I delete this and save it again,

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:59.400
I could come over here to my RStudio tracker, go to webinar on my way, and follow this 02.rmd,

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:06.200
and I could diff it. And since it's just plain text, it's very easy to read what's changed here.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:12.039
This is a git diff. And it's also easy to save on GitHub and that sort of thing. I'm not going

00:10:12.039 --> 00:10:17.080
to save this change because it's not a productive one. But this file and the other ones I'm showing

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:20.919
you today will be available at the short link. I'll share it again at the end of the webinar

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:25.799
that contains the materials for today. So we're looking at R Markdown file,

00:10:25.799 --> 00:10:34.039
and we see that it does have text here. It also has code, as we saw before. And it has a header

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:39.799
here, which is just some metadata about this file. The three types of content are demarcated

00:10:39.799 --> 00:10:45.559
by combinations of characters. That's what allows us to remain a plain text file. So if you have,

00:10:45.559 --> 00:10:48.599
if you want to have code in your file, you can surround it by three backticks.

00:10:49.159 --> 00:10:53.159
And any program that's aware of this file format will be able to recognize that there's

00:10:53.159 --> 00:10:57.719
executable code between those backticks. If you want to make a header, you can surround it by

00:10:57.719 --> 00:11:02.280
three dashes. And if you just want to write plain text, well, you can just write plain text.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.080
Although I have added some things here we'll talk about in a bit.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.039
Since this is a plain text file, you can open it in any text editor. But I would recommend

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:21.640
opening it in the RStudio editor because RStudio is designed in some ways to be a text editor for

00:11:21.640 --> 00:11:27.559
R Markdown files. The RStudio ID will automatically locate your code chunks in here, surrounded by

00:11:27.559 --> 00:11:33.159
the backticks, and will allow you to play them in that fashion I showed earlier. You can use this

00:11:33.159 --> 00:11:38.760
as you write your document to make the document effectively a notebook, a notebook interface.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:43.479
You can write your code, test it out, see if it does what you want. You can make the results go

00:11:43.479 --> 00:11:47.000
away if you don't like looking at them. But if you do like looking at them, they appear right here

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:52.760
next to your code. And then finally, the RStudio ID provides a knit button at the top of your

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:58.359
document, which allows you to use this plain text document to generate a new document that contains

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:06.919
the same content. At the moment, this document is set up to generate an HTML file. The HTML file has

00:12:06.919 --> 00:12:11.000
everything that's in the original document, including the code results. And in this case,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:16.520
I asked for R Markdown Studio not to include the code itself because I thought that'd be distracting.

00:12:16.599 --> 00:12:21.080
And you can see this is an HTML file. I could share it on a website or not. RStudio opens up

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:25.960
a preview so I could see the results and read them. And then if I look down here, I will see

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:30.679
that the actual file being previewed exists in my directory, and that's how I could take it and

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:36.200
share it and do something with it. Like I said, this document's set up to return HTML output,

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:40.520
but I could use the dropdown menu here, and I could create the same content as a PDF file.

00:12:41.479 --> 00:12:46.359
None of this really affects the plain text file. It creates a new separate file.

00:12:46.359 --> 00:12:51.239
This file is a PDF file, so if I was submitting to a journal perhaps or going to print this out,

00:12:51.239 --> 00:12:55.400
maybe I would use the PDF version instead of the HTML version. And then also I can make a

00:12:55.400 --> 00:13:00.919
Microsoft Word version. These are just some defaults that come in RStudio for making these

00:13:00.919 --> 00:13:06.119
files, but the idea behind R Markdown is you can use your plain text file to generate a report in

00:13:06.119 --> 00:13:11.080
a limitless number of formats. Each report will contain the same content, but it'll be adapted to

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:17.960
a new format. In this website, rmarkdown.rstudio.com slash formats is an enumerative list of the

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:23.320
options you have available for changing your plain text R Markdown files into new types of files.

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:28.200
Each of these are a function or an R package that can handle an R Markdown file and turn

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:32.359
into something new. You'll see you can make books, websites, blogs, packages,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.479
no shortage of things with R Markdown files. I'll click through to the Flex Dashboard one.

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:41.719
This is a way to make interactive, well, to make BI dashboards with R Markdown files.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.960
And, you know, if we look at some of the examples, maybe click through on one of them. Here's the

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:52.119
dashboard. It's made with R Markdown. If we look at the source code here, you can see,

00:13:52.119 --> 00:13:56.599
you know, here's the familiar R Markdown header separated by dashes. Here's some code chunks

00:13:56.599 --> 00:14:00.520
separated by backticks. And, you know, there's some formatting here that tells us what should

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:10.440
be in a column and whatnot. So, to recap the strengths of R Markdown, they're just plain text

00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:15.080
files, which makes them very portable, very usable. But you can embed code in them, which

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:21.000
makes them a true computational document. When you author an R Markdown file, you can use RStudio

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.840
ID to have a notebook interface if you like that experience for testing out your code.

00:14:25.239 --> 00:14:28.840
And then, finally, the whole idea behind R Markdown is that even though you're working

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:33.479
in a plain text file, you could generate a report that's not plain at all. And, in fact,

00:14:33.479 --> 00:14:38.520
the report can be in a variety of different formats. So, in my example, I just used the

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:44.760
knit button in R Markdown. But it is worth noting that you could also generate these

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:50.119
things programmatically. There is a function in the R Markdown package called render. And if you

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:59.320
send it the file path to your file, it will render the file for you programmatically. So,

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:03.320
you don't even need the RStudio ID, you just need R terminal to render these files. If you

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:06.679
do it programmatically, RStudio ID isn't going to open a preview or anything for you. But the

00:15:06.679 --> 00:15:11.239
file will be regenerated and it will be saved alongside your other file.

00:15:11.239 --> 00:15:23.479
So, now that you know the value proposition of R Markdown, let's look at the features of R

00:15:23.479 --> 00:15:28.039
Markdown that will be the most successful for making computational documents to share with

00:15:28.599 --> 00:15:34.679
consumers of a business nature. I'm not going to show you every single thing you need to learn

00:15:34.679 --> 00:15:38.760
to create R Markdown files, because I've already documented all of this in a self-paced tutorial

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:49.559
at this website. This tutorial takes about 45 minutes to maybe 90 minutes if you take your time

00:15:49.559 --> 00:15:54.359
to finish. And when you finish it, you will be an expert at R Markdown. It's very simple

00:15:54.359 --> 00:15:58.359
technology. You just have to learn the rules and they're easy to reapply. It will take you about

00:15:58.359 --> 00:16:03.000
the length of this webinar to learn this. But I'm not going to use the length of the webinar to

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:07.159
teach it. Instead, I want to focus on the more high value features here. I'm also not going to

00:16:07.159 --> 00:16:12.200
go very down into the weeds with R Markdown, because all of the details are documented at

00:16:12.200 --> 00:16:23.559
this website, bookdown.org. The book is available in its entirety for free online at this website,

00:16:23.559 --> 00:16:28.919
and it documents any questions that you might have about R Markdown. Instead, what I'm going

00:16:28.919 --> 00:16:34.679
to focus on are the features that I think will pay off the most for you watching today.

00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:39.799
All right. So first of all, first feature, how do you create an R Markdown file? If you want to

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:45.559
create an R Markdown file, go to the RStudio IDE, go to File, New File, R Markdown, and when the

